## 7. Value traits and deterministic behavior

## O4. Implement stable value traits

Every stable key type must implement:

```text
Debug
Clone
Copy
PartialEq
Eq
PartialOrd
Ord
Hash
```

This includes:

* all directly allocated keys;
* `SignalSourceKey<S>`;
* every erased key enum.

Generic key traits must not impose additional trait requirements on `S` beyond `SignalType`.

In particular, key traits must not depend on derives that accidentally require the marker to implement unrelated traits.

Required equality law for one concrete key type:

```text
key_a == key_b iff key_a.as_u128() == key_b.as_u128()
```

Required homogeneous ordering law:

```text
key_a.cmp(key_b) == key_a.as_u128().cmp(&key_b.as_u128())
```

The ordering exists only to provide deterministic canonical ordering.

It must not be documented or treated as:

* creation order;
* graph order;
* topology order;
* priority;
* age;
* ownership;
* causal order;
* allocation chronology across categories.

`Debug` must identify the concrete key type and provide useful opaque-value inspection. Exact debug wording is not a compatibility contract.

Do not implement:

* `Display`;
* `Default`;
* arithmetic operators;
* successor or predecessor operations;
* iteration;
* borrowing traits that expose the private field by reference;
* serialization derives.

---

## O5. Domain-separate structural hashing

Hashing must include the structural key category.

For signal-bearing key families, hashing must also include the signal kind.

Conceptually, the hashed input for one direct key is:

```text
structural category tag
signal kind tag when applicable
u128 payload
```

Examples of distinct hash domains include:

```text
NetworkKey
NodeKey
ConnectionKey
ModuleInstanceKey
ModuleInputKey<Level>
ModuleInputKey<Pulse>
ModuleOutputKey<Level>
ModuleOutputKey<Pulse>
InPortKey<Level>
InPortKey<Pulse>
OutPortKey<Level>
OutPortKey<Pulse>
ExternalInputKey<Level>
ExternalInputKey<Pulse>
ExternalOutputKey<Level>
ExternalOutputKey<Pulse>
```

Required properties:

* two equal values of one concrete key type feed identical data to a hasher;
* different payloads of one type feed different payload data;
* equal payloads in different structural categories feed category-distinct data;
* equal payloads in different signal kinds feed kind-distinct data;
* hash behavior does not depend on allocation history;
* hash behavior does not consult global state.

The resulting numeric output of any particular hasher is not a stable persistence digest and must not become a compatibility contract.

Tests should verify the domain-separated hash input using an appropriate test hasher rather than assuming that arbitrary distinct hash inputs can never collide under `DefaultHasher`.

